INTRODUCTION

Collected data is the fundamental element in prediction and has been widely used in different sectors for over 10 years. It is important to understand the behaviour of the data and to determine if there is any seasonality or trend, before making any prediction. Afterwards, most appropriate model should be used in order to make a successful prediction.

In this homework, hourly electric consumption data, which is token from EPIAS, is used to make 24 hour ahead forecasts with AR and MA models. First, the data aggregated to different frequencies and its behaviour is observed. Then, the pattern of the data is determined. The data is decomposed in order to deseasonilize and to detrend. After these, AR and MA models are used to make 24 hour ahead forecasts.

The electric consumption data is decomposed to hourly, daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly, and yearly levels. The data and associated ACF values are plotted to determine the pattern of electric consumption as shown below.

#decompose the series at different levels
elec_hourly<- xts(elec$cons,  order.by = date_elec)

By given figures above, it is found that there is a pattern with every 168 hours. The reason behind that is the ACF value of the hourly electric consumption data reaches its peak when the lag is equal to 24 and the ACF value of the weekly electric consumption data reaches its peak when the lag is equal to 7. The ACF values of other levels of data are relatively low and can be ignorable. The pattern is logical. For example, in the night, the electric consumption is very low whereas in noon it reaches peak. Therefore, 24 hours lag is suitable with general knowledge. Also, the days of the week have a significant role in electric consumption. For example, electric consumption on weekend is lower than the weekdays due to holiday.

Since the pattern is found, the data is decomposed. Then, the data is observed for different years as well as different months. It is found that electric consumption is increasing over the years. Also, the months in winter and september are the months with highest electricy consumption. It results from the heating or cooling processes.

Then, the data is decomposed. It is important to decide whether the time series is multiplicative or additive. The decomposition of additive and multiplicative time series are very similar, but the multiplicative time series gave a little more reliable result. However, the random part of the decompositions did not look like as expected. The problems are probably resulting from the national and regional holidays. It is hard to take remove these effects and different processes are needed. However, the test is done if the random part of the decompositions are white noise or not. Box test gave low p values for both decomposition, therefore models are accepted to make further manipulations. The data is deseasonilized and decomposed as it is multiplicative time series as shown below.

#deseasonalize
elec_deseasonalized <- elec_frequency/elec_dec_multip$seasonal
ts.plot(elec_deseasonalized, col=topo.colors(10), ylab="Gwh", main="Deseasonilized Electricity Consumption in Gwh")

acf(elec_deseasonalized)

#detrend
detrend <- elec_deseasonalized/elec_dec_multip$trend

acf(detrend, na.action = na.pass)

plot(elec_dec_multip$random, main="Random Noise of Electric Consumption Data", ylab="Random noise")

After these, both AR and MA models are applied to the data in order to find the best fit with by observing accociated AIC and BIC values. First of all, the AR model is applied with 3 different lag parameters. The AR model which has the lowest AIC or BIC is selected, since the lowest AIC values gives the best model. The same procedure is done for MA model. Then, the best AR and MA models are compared with one another. The MA model with window parameter 3 is the best model of these 6 models. The procedure is illustrated below.

ts.plot(elec_frequency, xlab = "Year", ylab = "Gwh",main="Electric Consumption in GWh")

model_ar1 <- arima(elec_frequency, order=c(1,0,0))

ar1_bic <- BIC(model_ar1)
model_ar2 <- arima(elec_frequency, order=c(2,0,0))

ar2_bic <- BIC(model_ar2)
model_ar3 <- arima(elec_frequency, order=c(3,0,0))

Lastly, the model is used to make 24 hours ahead forecast. However, somehow assumption is done for next 24 days. A mistake would have done. Because MA values are not good estimators for the long term, the assumption after 2 days ahead became constant.

model_ma3 <- arima(elec_frequency, order=c(0,0,3))
print(model_ma3)
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = elec_frequency, order = c(0, 0, 3))

model_fitted_ma3 <- elec_frequency - residuals(model_ma3)
elec_fig <- window(elec_frequency, start=c(2020))
ts.plot(elec_fig, xlab = "Year", ylab = "Gwh",main="Electricity Consumption in Gwh")
points(model_fitted_ma3, type = "l", col = 4, lty = 6)
model_fc_ar1 <- predict(model_ma3, n.ahead = 24)
print(model_fc_ar1)

CONCLUSION

The electricity consumption data is observed and it is found that the data has multiseasonality. Its patterin is 168 due to having hourly and weekly seasonality. Also, Then, the data is decomposed as a multiplicative time series.The data is deseasonalized and detrended according to formulae for multiplicative time series. The deseasonalized and decomposed data has still some pattern due to noises of special days. It is also observed that the electricity consumption is increasing over the years and has the highest value in summer months due to cooling devices.

In order to make 24 hours ahead predictions, the best model is selected by considering AIC and BIC values of AR and MA models. Then, the prediction is made. However, the model gave 24 days ahead prediction, instead of 24 hours prediction. Some mistake would have be done.
